<subSubSection id="C33E655CFFF2EF6DFF3D39B8FBB9BCD9" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9B36D7FFF2EF6DFF3D39B8FBB9BCD9" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFF3D39B8FEBDBD66" bold="true" box="[169,287,1532,1553]" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">Discussion.</emphasis>
—The scattered distribution of most 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFD4C39B9FC8FBD65" box="[728,813,1533,1554]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFD4C39B9FC8FBD65" box="[728,813,1533,1554]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">Hentzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in the western United States and Mexico, usually in riparian areas, suggests speciation events by the founder effect, with a few individuals being accidentally introduced (perhaps by storms) to isolated favorable habitats. The other possibility may be isolation of populations of more widely spread species (such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFE3F3AE9FDE3BDB5" box="[427,577,1708,1730]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" genus.bestMatchDistance="221" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmarum">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFE3F3AE9FDE3BDB5" box="[427,577,1708,1730]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">H. palmarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFDE03AE9FCA0BDB5" box="[628,770,1708,1730]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFDE03AE9FCA0BDB5" box="[628,770,1708,1730]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" genus.bestMatchDistance="20" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fimbriata">H. fimbriata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) in refugia because of desert expansion, followed by subsequent speciation events. The presence of 
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFDA93AACFCA5BD8A" box="[573,775,1767,1789]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFDA93AACFCA5BD8A" box="[573,775,1767,1789]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fimbriata">Hentzia fimbriata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
in Sycamore Canyon is an exception to the isolated populations in other parts of the southwesten USA and northwestern Mexico, as this species is widespread in Mexico. It is likely that its distribution follows the Sierra Madre and the watersheds of Mexican rivers draining into the Gulf of California. Sycamore Canyon, which drains into the Rio Altar in the Rio de la Concepcion drainage in Sonora, and where the U.S. specimens of 
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFB4D399AFACFBE84" box="[1241,1389,1501,1523]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFB4D399AFACFBE84" box="[1241,1389,1501,1523]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" genus.bestMatchDistance="246" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fimbriata">H. fimbriata</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
have been collected, is unusual in the variety of jumping spiders found there that are primarily associated with other geographical ranges. These include 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFBCE3A71FC6ABD1E" authority="Peckham &amp; Peckham 1885" authorityName="Peckham &amp; Peckham" authorityYear="1885" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Zygoballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufipes">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFBCE3A71FA87BD3B" box="[1114,1317,1589,1612]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">Zygoballus rufipes</emphasis>
Peckham &amp; Peckham 1885
</taxonomicName>
(Mexico and eastern United States), 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFAF23A17FC7BBDF0" authority="Pinter 1970" authorityName="Pinter" authorityYear="1970" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Phidippus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tux">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFAF23A17FA59BD1E" box="[1382,1531,1619,1641]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">Phidippus tux</emphasis>
Pinter 1970
</taxonomicName>
(central Mexico), and 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFB463A34FBA5BDD3" authority="Peckham &amp; Peckham 1892" authorityName="Peckham &amp; Peckham" authorityYear="1892" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Sarinda" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hentzi">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFB463A34FACFBDF0" box="[1234,1389,1648,1671]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">Sarinda hentzi</emphasis>
(Peckham &amp; Peckham 1892)
</taxonomicName>
(eastern United States) (all collected by the author). Because of the similar morphological features, future research on the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFB763A8EFA95BDA8" box="[1250,1335,1738,1759]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFB763A8EFA95BDA8" box="[1250,1335,1738,1759]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">Hentzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should include mitochondrial DNA analysis of as many species as possible in order to clear up the actual phylogenetic source and relationships of these species, especially in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFA1B3B66FA58BC4F" box="[1423,1530,1826,1848]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmarum">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFA1B3B66FA58BC4F" box="[1423,1530,1826,1848]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">palmarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. This is unfortunately beyond the scope of this paper and would require collection of fresh material from Cuba and Mexico, as well as the USA, even if limited to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D54FFF2EF6DFCC93BDCFC6BBCD9" box="[861,969,1944,1966]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Hentzia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palmarum">
<emphasis id="B950EAC5FFF2EF6DFCC93BDCFC6BBCD9" box="[861,969,1944,1966]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="77">palmarum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
